00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:37.300
teach here at Harvard--

00:03:37.300 --> 00:03:39.690
or take here at Harvard, sorry.

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:42.310
And it's one of
those classes where

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:43.810
everyone has an
impression, I think,

00:03:43.810 --> 00:03:45.220
before you enter the class.

00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:49.060
And it's a requirement for all
students going through pre-med,

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:53.930
going through any biology
or chemistry major.

00:03:53.930 --> 00:03:55.330
And this course
had traditionally

00:03:55.330 --> 00:03:57.530
been taught by Harvard
faculty and was

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:00.280
taught by one or two members
who rotated back and forth

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:03.430
and there was a very defined
system of doing things.

00:04:03.430 --> 00:04:05.380
And the other notable
aspect was that it

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:10.170
was the second semester to a
two semester sequence and so--

00:04:10.170 --> 00:04:12.190
I won't name the
class, but I think

00:04:12.190 --> 00:04:15.570
it might be easy to discern
what class this was.

00:04:15.570 --> 00:04:17.500
And so the students
in this class

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:22.900
were obviously very conscious,
very worried about doing well.

00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:25.545
I mean, most of them were very
interested in the material

00:04:25.545 --> 00:04:26.800
and it was--

00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:29.470
I would say most students are
probably certainly invested

00:04:29.470 --> 00:04:31.600
in actually learning,
but it was also

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:33.790
an environment
where students were

00:04:33.790 --> 00:04:36.740
focused on the outcome on
their transcript as well.

00:04:36.740 --> 00:04:39.860
And so this course was the
second semester in sequence

00:04:39.860 --> 00:04:42.310
and the first semester in
previous years have been done

00:04:42.310 --> 00:04:45.340
the standard way with
a lot of PowerPoint's.

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:46.300
It was very--

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:48.760
I guess, packaged
for students so there

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:51.894
was very little reading
textbooks, synthesizing notes,

00:04:51.894 --> 00:04:52.810
going to office hours.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:56.575
Everything was condensed to
one sheet of paper given out

00:04:56.575 --> 00:04:57.371
to you every week.

00:04:57.371 --> 00:04:58.620
PowerPoint slides were posted.

00:04:58.620 --> 00:05:00.820
They actually posted
annotated slides,

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:02.950
there were lecture
videos, so everything.

00:05:02.950 --> 00:05:04.908
You practically didn't
even have to go to class

00:05:04.908 --> 00:05:07.120
or read a textbook and you
could get that material.

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:09.190
And the problem sets
are very straightforward

00:05:09.190 --> 00:05:11.240
and everything was
well done in a way

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:14.142
that I think was overly
generous to the students.

00:05:14.142 --> 00:05:16.350
We actually had a professor
teach the second semester

00:05:16.350 --> 00:05:18.790
of the sequence who wasn't
a Harvard faculty member,

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:22.150
he was a visiting professor
and he decided to do everything

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:23.180
completely differently.

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:25.630
And so he took a very
traditionalist approach, which

00:05:25.630 --> 00:05:28.420
I think for the subject matter,
actually is not necessarily

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:29.550
a bad thing.

00:05:29.550 --> 00:05:31.510
Everything was done
at the chalkboard.

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:34.630
There were no slides,
there were no handouts,

00:05:34.630 --> 00:05:36.520
and he expected you
read the textbook,

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:38.320
simplifying things yourself.

00:05:38.320 --> 00:05:40.360
And there was a huge amount of--

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:44.440
I would say backlash
or unhappiness

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:46.100
with this form of teaching.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:47.750
He would also cold call and so--

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:49.360
I mean, it was a
large lecture class,

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:51.232
but he would call
on students and ask

00:05:51.232 --> 00:05:53.440
them to answer questions
regardless of whether or not

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:56.180
they were right or wrong, just
get their conversation going.

00:05:56.180 --> 00:05:59.556
And I think what we took
out of this was that--

00:05:59.556 --> 00:06:00.680
I think a couple of things.

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:04.810
The first is that students often
are very vocal about feedback,

00:06:04.810 --> 00:06:06.910
but sometimes that feedback
may not be directed

00:06:06.910 --> 00:06:08.560
at the quality of teaching.

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:10.365
And actually, I
personally-- and there

00:06:10.365 --> 00:06:12.031
were students in the
class who disagreed

00:06:12.031 --> 00:06:14.050
with a lot of the
majority voice, which

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:16.306
was that this professor had
no idea what he was doing,

00:06:16.306 --> 00:06:17.680
he was doing
everything wrong, it

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:21.340
wasn't supposed to be this way,
he wasn't teaching correctly.

00:06:21.340 --> 00:06:24.580
Cold calling, according to
many of my peers and friends,

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:28.570
was a dangerous or unsafe
tactic in the classroom.

00:06:28.570 --> 00:06:30.290
And there was a
lot of unhappiness

00:06:30.290 --> 00:06:32.140
with the way he
taught the class.

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:34.905
It was also markedly more
difficult then years before

00:06:34.905 --> 00:06:37.600
and I think that was also
another contributing factor.

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:41.950
And I think a lot of students
voiced disagreement with this.

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:44.590
They went to the
preceptor who's one

00:06:44.590 --> 00:06:46.870
of the support members of
the course who develops

00:06:46.870 --> 00:06:48.220
most of the curriculum.

00:06:48.220 --> 00:06:50.475
And halfway through
the course-- actually

00:06:50.475 --> 00:06:52.600
it was less than half way,
about a third of the way

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:54.670
through the course,
the professor actually

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:56.890
decided to stop cold
calling, to put a lot

00:06:56.890 --> 00:06:58.600
of the material on slides.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:02.235
And he was a senior faculty
member in another ivy league

00:07:02.235 --> 00:07:04.360
school so he'd been doing
this for many, many years

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:07.220
at that school-- he
was on sabbatical.

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:09.010
And it just, I think--

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:11.320
personally I felt
that that was I guess,

00:07:11.320 --> 00:07:13.690
a misuse, or at least
I thought it was--

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:15.874
the outcome was not
necessarily something

00:07:15.874 --> 00:07:18.040
positive because I think
his teaching methods forced

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:21.790
students to learn in a way
that was not necessarily

00:07:21.790 --> 00:07:24.634
what they had done before,
which I think is a good thing.

00:07:24.634 --> 00:07:26.800
I think he-- there was
pretty much consensus that he

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:28.909
was a good teacher,
but the problem

00:07:28.909 --> 00:07:30.700
was that people thought
the course was hard

00:07:30.700 --> 00:07:33.670
and that his teaching
style made it different

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:36.390
or forced people to
learn in a different way.

00:07:36.390 --> 00:07:39.670
And I think one thing
that I would say--

00:07:39.670 --> 00:07:41.170
I guess the conclusion
of the story

00:07:41.170 --> 00:07:44.190
is that oftentimes,
especially in places--

00:07:44.190 --> 00:07:46.300
Harvard, where students
are very concerned

00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:51.070
about the on-paper outcome of a
course, sometimes the feedback

00:07:51.070 --> 00:07:53.140
whether it's robust
or not can be

00:07:53.140 --> 00:07:55.660
directed at students
satisfaction with the course

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:57.410
rather than the
quality of teaching.

00:07:57.410 --> 00:07:59.425
And for a bunch of
20-year-olds who

00:07:59.425 --> 00:08:01.800
are worried about applying to
med school and grad school,

00:08:01.800 --> 00:08:04.930
sometimes it's hard to pull
those distinctions apart.

00:08:04.930 --> 00:08:07.840
But I do think that one
of the advantages or one

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:12.340
of the positive outcomes was
that there was a very robust

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:15.512
conversation about what people
thought and so-- to the point

00:08:15.512 --> 00:08:16.720
where the professor decided--

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:18.812
made the decision to
switch teaching styles.

00:08:18.812 --> 00:08:20.770
So at least I think that
conversation was there

00:08:20.770 --> 00:08:22.420
and people were aware.

00:08:22.420 --> 00:08:26.020
Whether or not that was a smart
choice is a separate question,

00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:31.320
but I think at least there
was that particular dialogue.

