00:11:02.270 --> 00:11:04.500
was a very unhealthy tactic.

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:08.490
He said, I can see that point,
I won't do that anymore.

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:10.670
Do you think his
transparency there

00:11:10.670 --> 00:11:14.150
was persuasive for your
colleagues in the class?

00:11:14.150 --> 00:11:16.906
You know, when he
said, this is--

00:11:16.906 --> 00:11:19.140
learning is hard and--

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:20.910
I can imagine he
may have said that.

00:11:20.910 --> 00:11:21.410
Right?

00:11:21.410 --> 00:11:24.050
I want you to take notes, you
need to generate knowledge

00:11:24.050 --> 00:11:24.920
on your own.

00:11:24.920 --> 00:11:25.920
Was that persuasive?

00:11:25.920 --> 00:11:29.810
Did that bring more of your
colleagues along to his style?

00:11:29.810 --> 00:11:33.352
I think it was very
important in explaining.

00:11:33.352 --> 00:11:35.810
I think a lot of students came
away from that understanding

00:11:35.810 --> 00:11:37.400
why he did things
the way he did.

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:40.080
I don't think it necessarily
convinced them or brought them

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:42.050
to his side.

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:45.670
I think even at the end of
the course-- and you know,

00:11:45.670 --> 00:11:46.250
this is--

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:47.350
this was two years ago.

00:11:47.350 --> 00:11:51.182
But I think it was a very
polarizing kind of cost

00:11:51.182 --> 00:11:52.640
in the sense of
there were students

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:53.690
who absolutely loved him.

00:11:53.690 --> 00:11:55.790
And he has a group of students
who stay in touch with him

00:11:55.790 --> 00:11:57.650
and he comes back to
Harvard every semester

00:11:57.650 --> 00:11:59.517
and we do journal
clubs with him.

00:11:59.517 --> 00:12:01.100
And so there were
students who thought

00:12:01.100 --> 00:12:03.020
he was one the best
science instructors ever

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:04.090
and then there are--

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:06.560
I'd say maybe 2/3
of students thought

00:12:06.560 --> 00:12:10.250
he was a good
instructor, but the class

00:12:10.250 --> 00:12:12.560
was something that they
absolutely despised

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:16.397
because of various reasons.

00:12:16.397 --> 00:12:18.230
I think people understood
what he was doing,

00:12:18.230 --> 00:12:19.805
I think he made that clear.

00:12:19.805 --> 00:12:22.700
But I don't think necessarily
people all came on board

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:24.170
or agreed.

00:12:24.170 --> 00:12:26.420
Maybe we'll take one more
question right now for Chris

00:12:26.420 --> 00:12:27.740
and then we'll come
back at the end.

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:28.240
Yes.

00:12:29.310 --> 00:12:33.770
When-- with the
fact that he decided

00:12:33.770 --> 00:12:36.660
to change his style
midway through,

00:12:36.660 --> 00:12:38.610
was there a discussion
among the students

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:44.560
about what that said about
the power of the students?

00:12:44.560 --> 00:12:48.130
And how did the students seem
to feel about that power,

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:50.610
if that ever came up in
a discussion afterwards?

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:51.550
Right.

00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:54.332
I think people realize--

00:12:54.332 --> 00:12:56.790
I think for him it was a little
bit different because a lot

00:12:56.790 --> 00:13:00.700
of faculty members, they
teach consistently and so

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:02.434
if a course goes
poorly one semester

00:13:02.434 --> 00:13:04.350
then that reflects on
next year down the line.

00:13:04.350 --> 00:13:06.340
But he was here for one
semester and that was it.

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:08.798
I don't think-- I think he had
a different type of pressure

00:13:08.798 --> 00:13:11.090
in terms of having
to cater to the pop--

00:13:11.090 --> 00:13:13.322
worrying about popularity
and where my Q scores will

00:13:13.322 --> 00:13:15.440
be seen as gone after this.

00:13:15.440 --> 00:13:18.640
I think the power dynamic
came more from the preceptor.

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:20.530
The preceptor for this
course was someone

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:22.117
who was immensely popular.

00:13:22.117 --> 00:13:24.700
I don't think there was a single
student who didn't absolutely

00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:25.200
love her.

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:27.400
And she was a good instructor.

00:13:27.400 --> 00:13:31.150
She also was part of the
first semester of the course.

00:13:31.150 --> 00:13:34.420
And I think students felt
very comfortable going to her.

00:13:34.420 --> 00:13:37.350
She was also a younger
faculty member,

00:13:37.350 --> 00:13:41.290
definitely more able to speak
to students about what they were

00:13:41.290 --> 00:13:44.110
feeling versus he was a very--
he was in a little bit more

00:13:44.110 --> 00:13:45.390
senior--

00:13:45.390 --> 00:13:48.430
older-- just a little
bit in terms of age

00:13:48.430 --> 00:13:50.840
farther removed from
college students.

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:53.620
And I think what happened
was all of the feedback

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:56.050
was channeled through
the preceptor who then I

00:13:56.050 --> 00:13:58.750
think ultimately there
had to be a conversation

00:13:58.750 --> 00:14:01.380
between the teaching staff,
her, and the professor,

00:14:01.380 --> 00:14:02.970
and they made those decisions.

00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:08.950
And I think maybe that speaks
more toward the importance

00:14:08.950 --> 00:14:10.650
of having different
voices on a teaching

00:14:10.650 --> 00:14:12.320
team as opposed to
the traditional,

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:14.731
there's one professor
and that's it,

00:14:14.731 --> 00:14:16.480
especially with large
Harvard courses when

00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:17.563
they are teaching fellows.

00:14:17.563 --> 00:14:21.040
There's preceptors, sometimes
there's a head teaching fellow.

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:23.620
Those parts of the system
often work together

00:14:23.620 --> 00:14:26.320
and communicate things
to them, push a course

00:14:26.320 --> 00:14:27.880
in a different direction.

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:29.340
Thanks.

00:14:29.340 --> 00:14:31.120
Thank you, Chris.

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:32.870
Brandon, want to
introduce yourself to us?

00:14:32.870 --> 00:14:33.910
Sure.

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:34.750
Hi, everyone.

00:14:34.750 --> 00:14:35.950
I'm Brandon.

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:39.310
I'm a third year PhD student
in Biomedical Sciences,

00:14:39.310 --> 00:14:42.340
currently based over
at the Longwood campus.

00:14:42.340 --> 00:14:44.120
I originally did my
undergrad in Toronto

00:14:44.120 --> 00:14:46.780
before coming here
for grad school.

00:14:46.780 --> 00:14:49.300
And while I've been
a teaching assistant

00:14:49.300 --> 00:14:51.970
for some graduate school
courses in my program,

00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:56.350
I thought the most
insightful events

00:14:56.350 --> 00:14:57.760
I could share
about my experience

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:01.277
so far with the
teacher-student relationship

00:15:01.277 --> 00:15:02.860
and how to evaluate
that, would really

00:15:02.860 --> 00:15:06.460
be in the context of
working in a professor's lab

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:10.330
and doing your thesis work
with a specific supervisor.

00:15:10.330 --> 00:15:15.970
The way our program works is
for the first one to two years,

00:15:15.970 --> 00:15:18.700
most students finish
their required courses

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:20.290
and at the end of
their first year

00:15:20.290 --> 00:15:24.130
they select a thesis lab in
which to do their thesis work

00:15:24.130 --> 00:15:27.730
and their thesis research.

00:15:27.730 --> 00:15:30.070
Over the course of my
undergraduate and graduate

00:15:30.070 --> 00:15:36.400
studies I've come to know maybe
between five and six professors

00:15:36.400 --> 00:15:38.200
on a scientific
and personal level

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:40.270
as I transited
through their lives.

00:15:40.270 --> 00:15:44.020
And I've had an
experience to feel out

00:15:44.020 --> 00:15:47.650
how different programs
and different scientists

00:15:47.650 --> 00:15:49.330
actually like to
be given feedback

00:15:49.330 --> 00:15:53.110
and like to hear how their
mentorship style is working.

00:15:53.110 --> 00:15:55.730
And I have to say, in
the majority of cases

00:15:55.730 --> 00:15:57.520
it's been that
there's no feedback

00:15:57.520 --> 00:15:59.740
and there's no
evaluation solicited,

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:02.920
and you have to be the
one to give it forward.

00:16:02.920 --> 00:16:06.190
In my undergrad, I worked
in three different labs

00:16:06.190 --> 00:16:10.240
and essentially the
PI or the professor

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:13.210
who was supervising
the lab would not ever

00:16:13.210 --> 00:16:15.730
ask for any feedback.

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:19.870
And it's a relationship where
you are a student in their lab

00:16:19.870 --> 00:16:23.110
and you are studying
under them, but it's

00:16:23.110 --> 00:16:24.500
a one way relationship.

00:16:24.500 --> 00:16:28.060
And while the PI may be
comfortable with receiving

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:29.860
feedback from you,
you have to be the one

00:16:29.860 --> 00:16:30.970
to initiate that process.

00:16:30.970 --> 00:16:35.590
And there is no formalized
method for delivering feedback

00:16:35.590 --> 00:16:37.210
to a professor.

00:16:37.210 --> 00:16:38.970
And when I've come
to Harvard, I've

00:16:38.970 --> 00:16:42.190
had a couple of different
experiences with this.

00:16:42.190 --> 00:16:46.030
I spent a short time
in a relatively new lab

00:16:46.030 --> 00:16:49.566
as part of one of my rotations
while I was selecting a thesis

00:16:49.566 --> 00:16:51.150
lab to work in.

00:16:51.150 --> 00:16:53.740
And she actually sat me down
at the end of my rotation

00:16:53.740 --> 00:16:57.460
and she asked how I felt
about her mentorship style

00:16:57.460 --> 00:16:59.530
and how she was running her lab.

00:16:59.530 --> 00:17:04.000
And I felt really gratified
to actually have a chance

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.119
to be asked for my feedback
instead of having to actually

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:08.980
take that step and
walk into their office

00:17:08.980 --> 00:17:11.369
and tell them something
I've been concerned about.

00:17:11.369 --> 00:17:17.319
And that actually, I felt was
a really big moment and really

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:19.990
something new that I
hadn't experienced before.

00:17:19.990 --> 00:17:22.024
And now that I'm
in a thesis lab,

00:17:22.024 --> 00:17:26.619
I've found myself working
with actually a professor who

00:17:26.619 --> 00:17:28.060
has really--

00:17:28.060 --> 00:17:30.820
he has an extremely
open door policy,

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:35.110
he essentially has just said,
be frank with me all the time.

00:17:35.110 --> 00:17:39.250
Any time I want to go into him
or his office with a concern,

00:17:39.250 --> 00:17:41.380
I know he's there
and ready to listen.

00:17:41.380 --> 00:17:44.380
But I also know other
students in situations

00:17:44.380 --> 00:17:47.705
where they aren't comfortable
giving feedback to their PI.

00:17:47.705 --> 00:17:51.650
They receive feedback on their
work, on their work styles,

00:17:51.650 --> 00:17:54.990
on the quality of their
data, et cetera, from the PI,

00:17:54.990 --> 00:17:57.180
but it never really
goes back the other way.

00:17:57.180 --> 00:17:59.870
And there's no--
aside from going

00:17:59.870 --> 00:18:02.930
to the administrative office and
asking them to really escalate

00:18:02.930 --> 00:18:07.140
your concerns, there's no
formalized and maybe not so

00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:09.870
serious way of giving feedback.

00:18:09.870 --> 00:18:13.290
Because once you
start that process

00:18:13.290 --> 00:18:16.050
it's pretty rigorous for
everyone involved and usually

00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:18.660
doesn't have a good outcome
for the relationship

00:18:18.660 --> 00:18:21.300
of the student and the PI.

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:24.855
I think there's definitely a lot
of ground for either discussion

00:18:24.855 --> 00:18:27.120
or improvement in that area.

00:18:27.120 --> 00:18:28.964
And as I understand,
it was also a topic

00:18:28.964 --> 00:18:30.130
in the keynote this morning.

00:18:33.010 --> 00:18:37.070
Any burning questions
for Brandon?

00:18:37.070 --> 00:18:37.749
Yeah.

00:18:37.749 --> 00:18:39.540
Just speaking with the
range of the faculty

00:18:39.540 --> 00:18:41.510
that you've had the
experience of working with,

00:18:41.510 --> 00:18:44.340
was there any observation of
a generational difference?

00:18:44.340 --> 00:18:44.840
Absolutely.

00:18:44.840 --> 00:18:47.173
In terms of the people who
were willing to take feedback

00:18:47.173 --> 00:18:49.260
and looking for it and
people who weren't?

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:51.072
Yes, absolutely.

00:18:51.072 --> 00:18:52.530
I would say the
ones that have been

00:18:52.530 --> 00:18:55.680
most receptive to
feedback, definitely

00:18:55.680 --> 00:18:57.530
are on the early
end of their career

00:18:57.530 --> 00:19:00.510
or just starting their lab.

00:19:00.510 --> 00:19:02.130
I wouldn't say that
older scientists

00:19:02.130 --> 00:19:04.260
are less receptive to feedback.

00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:08.490
I would say it's more difficult
to actually just give them back

00:19:08.490 --> 00:19:11.340
because they tend to
be more established,

00:19:11.340 --> 00:19:14.040
they tend to be a
little more distant,

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:15.990
maybe they're not
in the lab as much

00:19:15.990 --> 00:19:18.390
and it's hard to actually
track them down and express

00:19:18.390 --> 00:19:19.690
your concerns.

00:19:19.690 --> 00:19:23.537
But yeah, that definitely seems
to track with how long you've

00:19:23.537 --> 00:19:24.370
been in science for.

00:19:28.040 --> 00:19:31.490
I have one other
question for you.

00:19:31.490 --> 00:19:34.080
You mentioned this
should be done,

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:38.670
we need to solicit feedback
from mentees for their mentors.

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:43.190
And so there-- you could imagine
some kind of anonymous survey,

00:19:43.190 --> 00:19:45.590
but that doesn't really get
at the crux of what you're

00:19:45.590 --> 00:19:49.400
talking about, which is this is
a very individual relationship.

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:51.980
And while you've
heard your PI I'd say,

00:19:51.980 --> 00:19:55.050
I have an open door, come talk
to me and you've done that.

00:19:55.050 --> 00:19:57.500
I can imagine for other
students in the lab,

00:19:57.500 --> 00:20:01.430
they might feel less inclined
to really be open and honest

00:20:01.430 --> 00:20:04.430
and say all the things
that are on their mind.

00:20:04.430 --> 00:20:08.840
I wonder if you have
ideas for how we-- how

00:20:08.840 --> 00:20:12.920
do you encourage this
feedback in the lab setting?

00:20:12.920 --> 00:20:17.090
What interventions
could go in to help

00:20:17.090 --> 00:20:21.280
every student and their mentor
have these more productive

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:23.010
feedback conversations?

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:23.520
Right.

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:24.020
Yeah.

00:20:24.020 --> 00:20:26.430
That's a great question.

00:20:26.430 --> 00:20:29.750
I'm glad you brought up the
point of how to make things

00:20:29.750 --> 00:20:33.860
anonymous because in this
kind of relationship I really

00:20:33.860 --> 00:20:36.860
don't think you like--
there's no space to make--

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:40.620
to remove identifying
information because

00:20:40.620 --> 00:20:42.950
a PI will typically
have between five and--

00:20:42.950 --> 00:20:45.480
I'd say maybe four
or five students.

00:20:45.480 --> 00:20:49.340
If they're receiving feedback
it's not really useful to them

00:20:49.340 --> 00:20:50.270
if it's anonymous.

00:20:50.270 --> 00:20:53.410
And I think that having specific
information and having--

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:57.800
and actually educating the PI,
that perhaps it's not really

00:20:57.800 --> 00:21:01.100
criticism, but more
suggestions and improvements

00:21:01.100 --> 00:21:04.130
for the future, and
changing that mentality

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:06.800
is more important
than saying, oh,

00:21:06.800 --> 00:21:11.090
an anonymous student has
said, X, Y, and Z about you.

00:21:11.090 --> 00:21:13.730
And really the
only formal process

00:21:13.730 --> 00:21:18.240
I know right now, that where
students are asked for feedback

00:21:18.240 --> 00:21:21.960
on the lab they were in and how
that went is when students are

00:21:21.960 --> 00:21:24.440
at the end of program or
when they've graduated,

00:21:24.440 --> 00:21:27.510
which may not be the
most immediately helpful

00:21:27.510 --> 00:21:29.360
to the program, I think.

00:21:29.360 --> 00:21:35.450
And one idea I have had is
really maybe instituting

00:21:35.450 --> 00:21:37.100
some sort of--

00:21:37.100 --> 00:21:38.950
not so much formal,
but some sort

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:44.850
of set meeting with the
professor and with the student,

00:21:44.850 --> 00:21:47.040
maybe once a semester
or even once a year,

00:21:47.040 --> 00:21:49.910
would be I think more
than frequent enough where

00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:54.380
the explicit goal
is not for the PI

00:21:54.380 --> 00:21:58.002
to give feedback on the student,
which is typically how meetings

00:21:58.002 --> 00:21:59.710
with a PI and the
student go, but instead

00:21:59.710 --> 00:22:01.130
for it to go the other way.

00:22:01.130 --> 00:22:03.560
And for the explicit
goal of these meetings

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:07.310
to be for the student to express
how they've been experiencing

00:22:07.310 --> 00:22:11.060
the lab and how they feel
about mentorship styles

00:22:11.060 --> 00:22:14.350
and so on and so forth.

00:22:14.350 --> 00:22:15.498
Thank you.

