00:23:33.160 --> 00:23:36.180
and what motivated
us to take the class,

00:23:36.180 --> 00:23:40.735
as well as to say what you
wanted to get out of it, what

00:23:40.735 --> 00:23:42.955
we were hoping for
out of the readings

00:23:42.955 --> 00:23:44.850
and out of the discussions.

00:23:44.850 --> 00:23:48.390
Which I tend to be
someone who doesn't like--

00:23:48.390 --> 00:23:50.490
I didn't think about
that beforehand as much

00:23:50.490 --> 00:23:52.980
as I probably should have.

00:23:52.980 --> 00:23:55.890
But we all went around and
engaged in conversation

00:23:55.890 --> 00:23:58.450
with one another
about our backgrounds.

00:23:58.450 --> 00:24:01.860
And I think for me that was a--
it was just a great experience

00:24:01.860 --> 00:24:05.760
to hear not only from our
professor and his background,

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:07.260
but then hear from
other classmates

00:24:07.260 --> 00:24:10.287
and understand the perspective
they were coming from,

00:24:10.287 --> 00:24:12.120
and what they were
looking to get out of it,

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:13.869
and see how much that
matched up with what

00:24:13.869 --> 00:24:16.290
I was looking for, and
seeing that perspective

00:24:16.290 --> 00:24:18.510
and understanding.

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:21.390
From the very first
class, that we all

00:24:21.390 --> 00:24:23.910
have different perspectives,
we all have different goals,

00:24:23.910 --> 00:24:27.920
and how do we help each
other to reach those.

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:33.750
And so for me that was a very,
welcome to HLS kind of moment.

00:24:33.750 --> 00:24:37.290
And I'm really excited to
see how this semester goes

00:24:37.290 --> 00:24:40.440
and how our conversations
in the smaller group

00:24:40.440 --> 00:24:44.060
feed into that
narrative and are--

00:24:44.060 --> 00:24:45.900
our syllabus has now
been formed so we

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:49.590
know what's happening
throughout this semester.

00:24:49.590 --> 00:24:51.870
But it does seem-- and
even in our conversation

00:24:51.870 --> 00:24:54.212
within the first
meeting of the class,

00:24:54.212 --> 00:24:56.170
you could tell that he
was asking us and trying

00:24:56.170 --> 00:24:57.810
to pull from our
different perspectives

00:24:57.810 --> 00:24:59.960
and directing questions
at certain people who

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:02.910
might have certain
experiences and then directing

00:25:02.910 --> 00:25:03.870
others at others.

00:25:08.010 --> 00:25:09.465
Any questions for Signa?

00:25:14.330 --> 00:25:17.422
I would love to do
that myself, is--

00:25:17.422 --> 00:25:18.130
to leave it open.

00:25:18.130 --> 00:25:23.700
But I wondered was this
invitation covering

00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:26.190
the material and the
kinds of questions,

00:25:26.190 --> 00:25:27.600
the contents, so to speak?

00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:32.220
Or did it also incorporate,
how should I evaluate you?

00:25:32.220 --> 00:25:35.840
How do we define whether
we've learned anything?

00:25:35.840 --> 00:25:37.660
Was that also open
for discussion?

00:25:37.660 --> 00:25:39.080
Or was it really just content?

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:40.830
And maybe this is
different because you're

00:25:40.830 --> 00:25:42.790
in a law school than
an undergraduate,

00:25:42.790 --> 00:25:45.540
but you can imagine at
the undergraduate level

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:48.740
at some point some things
are not negotiable or open.

00:25:48.740 --> 00:25:51.520
How did it work in that class?

00:25:51.520 --> 00:25:52.950
Because this is
one credit class--

00:25:52.950 --> 00:25:54.616
it's called a reading
group and it tends

00:25:54.616 --> 00:25:56.280
to be credit fail
so professors have

00:25:56.280 --> 00:26:00.280
a very open
experience with that,

00:26:00.280 --> 00:26:03.060
they can pretty much
do whatever they want.

00:26:03.060 --> 00:26:05.277
The conversation
definitely was more of,

00:26:05.277 --> 00:26:06.360
what are you looking for--

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:08.780
less in how he would be
evaluating us, but more

00:26:08.780 --> 00:26:11.950
on how he structures
our reading the content,

00:26:11.950 --> 00:26:13.570
making sure that for--

00:26:13.570 --> 00:26:18.710
this wasn't necessarily like
a waste of time class for us.

00:26:18.710 --> 00:26:21.160
He wanted it to be
specific to what

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:25.650
we needed out of it, what we
were trying to get out of it.

00:26:25.650 --> 00:26:27.120
Thank you.

00:26:27.120 --> 00:26:28.600
Disha?

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:29.220
Hi, everybody.

00:26:29.220 --> 00:26:29.920
I'm Disha.

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:32.540
I am an undergraduate at
Harvard College studying

00:26:32.540 --> 00:26:33.970
Chemical and Physical Biology.

00:26:33.970 --> 00:26:37.780
I'm a junior with a secondary
in Computer Science.

00:26:37.780 --> 00:26:39.220
And I've taken a
bunch of classes

00:26:39.220 --> 00:26:41.350
in the Humanities,
some in Engineering

00:26:41.350 --> 00:26:45.190
so I can really speak to a
pretty broad, diverse array

00:26:45.190 --> 00:26:48.790
of what Harvard
College has to offer.

00:26:48.790 --> 00:26:51.040
On campus here, I'm also
a course facilitator

00:26:51.040 --> 00:26:53.124
for Internal Life Sciences
and I am a peer advisor

00:26:53.124 --> 00:26:55.498
for the incoming freshmen so
I've talked to a lot of them

00:26:55.498 --> 00:26:57.510
about their experiences
choosing courses.

00:26:57.510 --> 00:26:59.362
And I also teach
dance and poetry

00:26:59.362 --> 00:27:00.820
to Cambridge Middle
School children

00:27:00.820 --> 00:27:05.035
so I understand how hard the
teaching side of it is as well.

00:27:05.035 --> 00:27:07.660
I would just like to start with
an anecdote that's a little bit

00:27:07.660 --> 00:27:08.451
similar to Chris's.

00:27:08.451 --> 00:27:12.940
It's about a large Life
Science course here on campus

00:27:12.940 --> 00:27:15.310
and my experience with
the mid-year evaluation

00:27:15.310 --> 00:27:19.080
and the students
experience as a whole.

00:27:19.080 --> 00:27:21.000
This course is pretty
required for a lot

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.090
of students pursuing both
biology and chemistry,

00:27:24.090 --> 00:27:26.530
but also pre-med.

00:27:26.530 --> 00:27:28.260
It was taught this year--

00:27:28.260 --> 00:27:31.830
that I was taking it by a new
faculty member who was young,

00:27:31.830 --> 00:27:33.360
still establishing
himself, still

00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:36.400
learning the ropes of
how to teach at Harvard.

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:39.100
And there were mixed reviews
of his teaching style

00:27:39.100 --> 00:27:40.740
early on in the class.

00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:43.020
There are a lot of
people who were wanting

00:27:43.020 --> 00:27:45.720
to be able to ask more questions
during the lecture, which

00:27:45.720 --> 00:27:47.850
considering it's a very
large lecture style class,

00:27:47.850 --> 00:27:49.530
it's pretty difficult
to take questions

00:27:49.530 --> 00:27:51.510
within just the one
hour that the professor

00:27:51.510 --> 00:27:52.720
has for instruction.

00:27:52.720 --> 00:27:54.690
So it's understandable.

00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:57.100
But there was a lot
of feedback and push

00:27:57.100 --> 00:27:58.980
during the mid-year
evaluation time

00:27:58.980 --> 00:28:01.080
for him to be able to
take more questions,

00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:03.820
for the lecture slides to
be printed on larger papers

00:28:03.820 --> 00:28:06.120
because we had all these
chemical reactions that should

00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:08.090
probably have been printed
on one slide instead

00:28:08.090 --> 00:28:09.990
of two slides per page.

00:28:09.990 --> 00:28:13.020
For him to hold more
frequent office hours.

00:28:13.020 --> 00:28:16.540
Basically the way he approached
this was very upfront.

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:19.030
I talked to the
preceptor of the course

00:28:19.030 --> 00:28:21.242
later on person-to-person
and office hours.

00:28:21.242 --> 00:28:23.700
And she basically told me that
he had gone through and read

00:28:23.700 --> 00:28:26.096
every single one of
the 300 evaluations

00:28:26.096 --> 00:28:27.720
that every single
student had submitted

00:28:27.720 --> 00:28:29.904
during the mid-year
evaluation period.

00:28:29.904 --> 00:28:31.320
And he took those
quite personally

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:33.926
sometimes because they
were quite hard to read.

00:28:33.926 --> 00:28:35.550
It was his first year
teaching so there

00:28:35.550 --> 00:28:38.280
was a lot of pretty
candid feedback.

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:41.430
But he went through and
then personally addressed

00:28:41.430 --> 00:28:43.015
the entire class
in a lecture that

00:28:43.015 --> 00:28:44.640
actually happened on
my birthday, which

00:28:44.640 --> 00:28:47.250
is around the mid-year time.

00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:50.310
With the feedback that basically
he had gotten and said,

00:28:50.310 --> 00:28:53.360
these are the things that I
am going to do differently.

00:28:53.360 --> 00:28:55.319
I am going to take more
questions during class.

00:28:55.319 --> 00:28:57.526
The slides are going to be
printed in this new format

00:28:57.526 --> 00:28:59.940
so it's easier for you guys
to handle them and understand

00:28:59.940 --> 00:29:00.780
them.

00:29:00.780 --> 00:29:03.330
This is how office hours
are going to work now.

00:29:03.330 --> 00:29:07.230
Basically he stood there and
addressed every single one

00:29:07.230 --> 00:29:09.900
of our concerns in person.

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:12.540
And it was very validating
to hear that a professor

00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:14.107
for this very large class--

00:29:14.107 --> 00:29:15.690
professor on tenure
track who was just

00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:19.290
getting used to style
of teaching at Harvard

00:29:19.290 --> 00:29:21.830
was willing to hear
what we had to say,

00:29:21.830 --> 00:29:24.780
and was willing to hear
the sort of evaluations

00:29:24.780 --> 00:29:28.530
that we had for him, and really
took the time to critically

00:29:28.530 --> 00:29:30.210
read everything that we said.

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:31.980
That being said,
I do think that--

00:29:31.980 --> 00:29:34.260
echoing something that
Chris said earlier, not

00:29:34.260 --> 00:29:38.160
all the student evaluations that
I believe that courses receive

00:29:38.160 --> 00:29:41.480
are always in the best interest
of the students' learning,

00:29:41.480 --> 00:29:42.540
in a sense.

00:29:42.540 --> 00:29:46.590
I've also taken a class in the
humanities that is primarily

00:29:46.590 --> 00:29:49.630
for freshmen and the
course is very challenging.

00:29:49.630 --> 00:29:52.830
We read Joyce's
Ulysses in three weeks.

00:29:52.830 --> 00:29:58.350
And we read Plato and
Macbeth and all these books,

00:29:58.350 --> 00:29:59.310
like once--

00:29:59.310 --> 00:30:01.110
like one book per
week basically.

00:30:01.110 --> 00:30:03.450
It's a time-intensive
reading, intensive class.

00:30:03.450 --> 00:30:05.970
And I think my year
was the second year

00:30:05.970 --> 00:30:07.110
that it was being run.

00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:09.810
And the year afterward it was
significantly easier I believe.

00:30:09.810 --> 00:30:12.470
The workload was easier,
the final was easier.

00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:14.890
And because of that I
think the course actually

00:30:14.890 --> 00:30:17.190
became less rich for the
students who were involved

00:30:17.190 --> 00:30:19.260
because the faculty
had decided to take

00:30:19.260 --> 00:30:22.020
into account the evaluations
that were asking for the class

00:30:22.020 --> 00:30:25.060
to be less time and less
of a stressful burden

00:30:25.060 --> 00:30:27.310
on the students
come finals period.

00:30:27.310 --> 00:30:30.250
But I really think that I got a
lot more out of the course when

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:31.590
it was more challenging.

00:30:31.590 --> 00:30:35.070
I think in a sense,
students do have the power

00:30:35.070 --> 00:30:37.300
to shape a lot about
how the course works,

00:30:37.300 --> 00:30:40.500
but like Chris was saying
earlier, sometimes we

00:30:40.500 --> 00:30:43.620
do worry a little bit too
much about the time constraint

00:30:43.620 --> 00:30:46.110
or what it will do
towards GPA or the fact

00:30:46.110 --> 00:30:49.080
that it's just a requirement
for our concentration.

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:51.550
I think it's worth having
those candid conversations

00:30:51.550 --> 00:30:54.230
and keeping that in mind
with the evaluations.

00:30:57.760 --> 00:30:58.890
Thanks, Disha.

00:30:58.890 --> 00:31:02.950
You mentioned for
today that you really

00:31:02.950 --> 00:31:06.780
value the Q Guide
as a student and yet

00:31:06.780 --> 00:31:09.280
you just talked about
this discrepancy that

00:31:09.280 --> 00:31:14.040
could exist between the
popularity of the professor

00:31:14.040 --> 00:31:17.700
and maybe even how good he
or she-- how charismatic

00:31:17.700 --> 00:31:21.630
he is in front of a classroom
with what you actually learn

00:31:21.630 --> 00:31:24.840
in the class and that
those two may not always

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:26.370
correlate highly.

00:31:26.370 --> 00:31:28.500
I wonder what it is
from the student side

00:31:28.500 --> 00:31:31.920
that you value in the Q. What
do you look for when you are

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:36.497
shopping a course and
deciding, does this

00:31:36.497 --> 00:31:38.080
look like something
I'm interested in?

00:31:38.080 --> 00:31:41.817
What are you looking for in
this other students feedback?

00:31:41.817 --> 00:31:43.650
I think the Q is
absolutely something that's

00:31:43.650 --> 00:31:45.670
pretty critical for a
lot of students because--

00:31:45.670 --> 00:31:47.253
especially freshmen,
they don't always

00:31:47.253 --> 00:31:49.080
have a whole lot
of places to learn

00:31:49.080 --> 00:31:51.454
about what a class is like
before they go into a shopping

00:31:51.454 --> 00:31:52.870
week.

00:31:52.870 --> 00:31:55.570
That being said, I do take the
Q Guide with a grain of salt

00:31:55.570 --> 00:31:58.500
sometimes because the
evaluations that students give

00:31:58.500 --> 00:32:00.450
are anatomised
and you don't know

00:32:00.450 --> 00:32:04.950
exactly the background of some
students going into the class.

00:32:04.950 --> 00:32:07.410
Say for example, I came from
a very strong life sciences

00:32:07.410 --> 00:32:08.780
background in high school.

00:32:08.780 --> 00:32:11.074
I've taken-- I took organic
chemistry in high school

00:32:11.074 --> 00:32:12.740
and because of that,
my experience going

00:32:12.740 --> 00:32:14.850
into organic chemistry
in freshman year

00:32:14.850 --> 00:32:16.600
was very different
from some of the things

00:32:16.600 --> 00:32:18.390
that the Q Guide was
saying, which was like,

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:20.340
oh, this class is awful, it's
going to wreck your life,

00:32:20.340 --> 00:32:21.890
it's going to be
way too difficult

00:32:21.890 --> 00:32:24.500
for you to take as a freshman.

00:32:24.500 --> 00:32:27.210
It's just something
to keep in mind.

00:32:27.210 --> 00:32:29.590
And I do think that
there are classes that

00:32:29.590 --> 00:32:33.936
will be rated highly that are--

00:32:33.936 --> 00:32:36.300
that I think potentially are
rated highly just because

00:32:36.300 --> 00:32:40.749
of the personality of the
professor or because of--

00:32:40.749 --> 00:32:42.790
for example, there's one
particular science class

00:32:42.790 --> 00:32:45.330
that normally gets really
pretty high Q scores,

00:32:45.330 --> 00:32:47.790
but gets that because the
professor is really funny, not

00:32:47.790 --> 00:32:50.670
necessarily because the class
is particularly well taught,

00:32:50.670 --> 00:32:53.910
it's just because her
lectures are enjoyable.

00:32:53.910 --> 00:32:55.770
When I look at the Q
Guide as a student,

00:32:55.770 --> 00:33:00.360
I really value to find out the
Q shows the amount of hours that

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:02.250
go into the class per week.

00:33:02.250 --> 00:33:04.220
Because as busy
students, everyone

00:33:04.220 --> 00:33:06.950
wants to know how to budget
their time on average.

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:09.270
And I also really value what
the students individually

00:33:09.270 --> 00:33:11.400
have to say.

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:13.050
I think faculty
sometimes get asked

00:33:13.050 --> 00:33:14.710
like is the Q even useful?

00:33:14.710 --> 00:33:16.929
They wonder whether the
students even use it.

00:33:16.929 --> 00:33:17.970
I think it's very useful.

00:33:17.970 --> 00:33:23.020
I think I have not really seen
any courses that don't release

00:33:23.020 --> 00:33:24.830
Q scores, but when
they don't it makes

00:33:24.830 --> 00:33:27.330
me wonder what is there about
the course that I should know?

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:29.790
What is it that
the faculty doesn't

00:33:29.790 --> 00:33:31.156
want me to see basically?

00:33:34.090 --> 00:33:34.934
Umm so yeah.

00:33:39.260 --> 00:33:42.420
I have a question for Signa
kind of informed by the comment

00:33:42.420 --> 00:33:44.130
that Disha just made.

00:33:44.130 --> 00:33:46.250
I've never taken
a law class and so

00:33:46.250 --> 00:33:50.020
I don't know what your standard
is for giving evaluation

00:33:50.020 --> 00:33:50.540
feedbacks.

00:33:50.540 --> 00:33:53.046
And nothing just about Harvard
and the experience so far,

00:33:53.046 --> 00:33:55.670
when you think back about any of
the work that you did earlier,

00:33:55.670 --> 00:33:58.390
how do you actually
give feedback?

00:33:58.390 --> 00:34:00.330
Is it just the end
of the semester?

00:34:00.330 --> 00:34:03.255
Eval, and then how do you
know if faculty factor that in

00:34:03.255 --> 00:34:06.400
or keep them accountable to it.

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:08.090
The law school
model is typically--

00:34:08.090 --> 00:34:09.389
you get feedback at the end.

00:34:09.389 --> 00:34:13.820
It's something like a
Q Guide system where--

00:34:13.820 --> 00:34:16.050
for GW for instance,
you would rank

00:34:16.050 --> 00:34:20.389
the hours, the effectiveness
of the lectures,

00:34:20.389 --> 00:34:24.810
teachers knowledge of the
course, student engagement

00:34:24.810 --> 00:34:25.790
participation.

00:34:25.790 --> 00:34:29.710
And then you had a box where you
could give individual comments

00:34:29.710 --> 00:34:32.449
and feedbacks either to the
teacher and then just students

00:34:32.449 --> 00:34:35.360
who are considering the class.

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:38.480
The second-- that tends to
be pretty much everywhere.

00:34:38.480 --> 00:34:41.810
I will say, one thing I was
so shocked about Harvard Law

00:34:41.810 --> 00:34:43.909
is that apparently
it's not online.

00:34:43.909 --> 00:34:45.949
I think they're moving
towards that direction,

00:34:45.949 --> 00:34:49.100
but I will say, choosing
classes for the semester was

00:34:49.100 --> 00:34:52.590
terrible trying to
figure out what to take.

00:34:52.590 --> 00:34:55.230
What do I know about
these professors?

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:57.620
Some of it-- they have
some of it online,

00:34:57.620 --> 00:35:01.240
but ultimately it's just
not all together in a space

00:35:01.240 --> 00:35:03.910
that I think it
really should be.

00:35:03.910 --> 00:35:06.260
But basically trying--

00:35:06.260 --> 00:35:07.460
I use it a lot.

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:11.479
I use that feedback, especially
the individual comments at GW

00:35:11.479 --> 00:35:13.520
based on what students
have said about the class.

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:16.370
If they say, if you--

00:35:16.370 --> 00:35:19.370
government contracts-- if
you have a broad interest

00:35:19.370 --> 00:35:21.770
in this person's
a person for you

00:35:21.770 --> 00:35:23.764
if you want something
that's more in depth

00:35:23.764 --> 00:35:25.680
or specific or you know
that this is something

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:29.420
that you want to do, go
with a different professor.

00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:34.140
Hearing that feedback and then
figuring it out is so helpful.

00:35:34.140 --> 00:35:36.440
But in terms of
teacher-- the feedback

00:35:36.440 --> 00:35:39.449
that teachers get and professors
get from those evaluations,

00:35:39.449 --> 00:35:41.240
we have no idea whether
or not they take it

00:35:41.240 --> 00:35:42.290
into consideration.

00:35:42.290 --> 00:35:44.404
And I will say something
for me as a student--

00:35:44.404 --> 00:35:46.070
and I think a lot of
my other classmates

00:35:46.070 --> 00:35:50.120
think this is well, is it that
the tenure system sort of--

00:35:50.120 --> 00:35:51.590
you write an
evaluation, especially

00:35:51.590 --> 00:35:56.832
for your 1L doctrinal
classes where you say,

00:35:56.832 --> 00:35:58.790
I didn't understand a
thing that this professor

00:35:58.790 --> 00:36:00.800
was saying to me all semester.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:03.540
I went to office hours,
he was grouchy and mean

00:36:03.540 --> 00:36:06.100
and didn't help,
and I left the class

00:36:06.100 --> 00:36:09.300
just being like, I
couldn't do this subject.

00:36:09.300 --> 00:36:11.160
And then you know
nothing changes

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:14.510
because they've said
in the past, whatever,

00:36:14.510 --> 00:36:17.870
you guys write whatever you
want in our course evals.

00:36:17.870 --> 00:36:22.107
And there's no driving force for
them to change their curriculum

00:36:22.107 --> 00:36:25.460
or change their teaching
methodology, which

00:36:25.460 --> 00:36:27.830
is something that's
frustrating on a student.

00:36:27.830 --> 00:36:29.570
And especially when--

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:31.239
I would say for
the first year you

00:36:31.239 --> 00:36:33.280
don't get a choice in the
teachers and professors

00:36:33.280 --> 00:36:35.400
that you get, your
placed into a class.

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:38.870
And you have to figure out
what that professors system is

00:36:38.870 --> 00:36:42.800
and go with it, and
it's on you to do that.

00:36:42.800 --> 00:36:45.170
And so when you get to
the end of the course,

00:36:45.170 --> 00:36:46.940
a lot of the time
it comes down to you

00:36:46.940 --> 00:36:48.842
ranting about all
of the injustices

00:36:48.842 --> 00:36:51.300
that you feel like you went
through throughout the semester

00:36:51.300 --> 00:36:53.279
and not necessarily
thinking that it's actually

00:36:53.279 --> 00:36:55.820
going to have any effect on the
people who are going to come.

00:36:58.460 --> 00:36:59.660
Thank you.

00:36:59.660 --> 00:37:02.464
Thank you all for all
of your presentations.

00:37:02.464 --> 00:37:04.130
One thing I was hearing
across the board

00:37:04.130 --> 00:37:08.590
was just how important or
how positive of an experience

00:37:08.590 --> 00:37:10.210
it was for you to
feel recognized,

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:13.200
feel like your voices mattered.

00:37:13.200 --> 00:37:17.630
I'm coming as a French
professor so the opposite of--

00:37:17.630 --> 00:37:19.340
I don't do lectures.

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:23.270
I'm teaching a seminar,
that means once a week.

00:37:23.270 --> 00:37:31.020
In terms of what
format to choose,

00:37:31.020 --> 00:37:35.090
or what format what might
work in making students

00:37:35.090 --> 00:37:37.550
feel like their voices
have been heard,

00:37:37.550 --> 00:37:40.370
I hesitate to devote one--

00:37:40.370 --> 00:37:42.380
the semester's not
very long, it's

00:37:42.380 --> 00:37:45.185
only about 12 teachable weeks
because the first week you

00:37:45.185 --> 00:37:47.300
can't really do
anything with shopping.

00:37:47.300 --> 00:37:50.570
And I hesitate to
take class time out,

00:37:50.570 --> 00:37:54.860
which I don't have that much
of to go over the evaluations

00:37:54.860 --> 00:37:59.480
because that means we're reading
one last novel that semester.

00:37:59.480 --> 00:38:06.040
Can you think of alternatives
to taking class time away

00:38:06.040 --> 00:38:12.961
to go over student feedback
that might still make you feel

00:38:12.961 --> 00:38:14.949
recognized and listened to?

00:38:19.919 --> 00:38:23.270
I think students do
read their emails

00:38:23.270 --> 00:38:27.290
and do respond to office hours.

00:38:27.290 --> 00:38:29.360
I think if there
were opportunities

00:38:29.360 --> 00:38:31.750
to go talk to you in office
hours about feedback,

00:38:31.750 --> 00:38:33.240
that might also be an option.

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:35.240
I don't necessarily
think that it

00:38:35.240 --> 00:38:37.610
need to in lecture
or in your seminar

00:38:37.610 --> 00:38:40.204
because I do understand that
seminars are very limited time

00:38:40.204 --> 00:38:42.370
and what students value at
seminars is the learning,

00:38:42.370 --> 00:38:46.501
not necessarily talking about
the feedback of the learning.

00:38:46.501 --> 00:38:47.000
So

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:49.166
I think an email communication
is also totally fine.

00:38:49.166 --> 00:38:52.190
I've had professors who've
done that in the past.

00:38:52.190 --> 00:38:54.000
And we do read that
because obviously,

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:55.833
when your professor is
sending you something

00:38:55.833 --> 00:38:58.480
you should probably
check that it is.

00:38:58.480 --> 00:39:02.710
And maybe, I don't know, like
candid office hours may also

00:39:02.710 --> 00:39:06.830
be an option, office hours
themed around the feedback.

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:09.280
I would second that,
particularly with office hours.

00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:12.100
I've had professors
who after I ask

00:39:12.100 --> 00:39:14.285
a question will ask how
do I feel about the class,

00:39:14.285 --> 00:39:17.260
how do I feel like it's
going, and that opens up

00:39:17.260 --> 00:39:18.290
the conversation.

00:39:18.290 --> 00:39:19.920
And there are
definitely professors

00:39:19.920 --> 00:39:23.330
where I know to be sort of
more, no, everything-- you know,

00:39:23.330 --> 00:39:24.630
everything's fine.

00:39:24.630 --> 00:39:26.091
Ultimately, more positive.

00:39:26.091 --> 00:39:27.507
And there are other
professors who

00:39:27.507 --> 00:39:29.090
I know are really
looking for the more

00:39:29.090 --> 00:39:30.670
constructive criticism.

00:39:30.670 --> 00:39:33.640
But having the opportunity
and having a professor prompt

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:36.200
you to give that in a
more one-on-one setting

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:38.210
makes it feel like
you're actually

00:39:38.210 --> 00:39:41.200
having your voice heard.

00:39:41.200 --> 00:39:43.240
Maybe a companion
question that--

00:39:43.240 --> 00:39:44.890
and I know a couple
of you mentioned

00:39:44.890 --> 00:39:47.200
that you've also
taught and so you've

00:39:47.200 --> 00:39:51.410
been on the other side of
this system of evaluations.

00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:59.140
And so have you ever as
a teacher, as a student,

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:02.722
have you been given a
mid-course evaluation?

00:40:02.722 --> 00:40:04.810
So from the student
side where it really

00:40:04.810 --> 00:40:07.270
didn't ask something
about something

00:40:07.270 --> 00:40:09.730
that you cared deeply about?

00:40:09.730 --> 00:40:12.370
And did that-- how did
that make you feel?

00:40:12.370 --> 00:40:14.210
Were you frustrated by that?

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:16.120
And then on the other--
and as a student

00:40:16.120 --> 00:40:18.940
did you ever answer
something on a mid-course

00:40:18.940 --> 00:40:21.250
and not see it
addressed in the class

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:24.220
and what did you
feel about that?

00:40:24.220 --> 00:40:28.110
And then from the
teacher side of things,

00:40:28.110 --> 00:40:32.730
can you think about
why that might happen?

00:40:32.730 --> 00:40:37.760
That disconnect of that either
you don't get asked something

00:40:37.760 --> 00:40:41.670
or that you don't have
an opportunity to--

00:40:41.670 --> 00:40:44.980
that you don't hear that your
feedback was really addressed?

00:40:48.670 --> 00:40:50.400
I've been-- I don't--

00:40:50.400 --> 00:40:53.060
we don't have mid-year
for PCMP, right?

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:53.881
We didn't do that.

00:40:54.380 --> 00:41:01.990
OK, yeah, so I don't have a
specific answer to the question

00:41:01.990 --> 00:41:03.290
of mid-year evaluations.

00:41:03.290 --> 00:41:06.080
But I've been both
a student and a TA

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:09.120
for the second year
this time around.

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:11.230
In the first year
molecular biology

00:41:11.230 --> 00:41:13.780
graduate course for my program.

00:41:13.780 --> 00:41:16.750
I've seen the exact same
course for three years

00:41:16.750 --> 00:41:21.820
now from both sides
and I think something

00:41:21.820 --> 00:41:24.750
that the students sometimes--

00:41:24.750 --> 00:41:27.730
when I was a student and
hearing feedback from students

00:41:27.730 --> 00:41:31.150
in my section that I lead at
discussion section every two

00:41:31.150 --> 00:41:34.720
weeks, is that
sometimes students

00:41:34.720 --> 00:41:39.550
fail to really see the
reality of running a course.

00:41:39.550 --> 00:41:43.472
And sometimes just during
informal, maybe halfway

00:41:43.472 --> 00:41:45.430
through the semester,
I'll check in with people

00:41:45.430 --> 00:41:47.700
and see how my
students are doing.

00:41:47.700 --> 00:41:51.010
They'll bring up
points such as say,

00:41:51.010 --> 00:41:52.690
changing the format
of problem sets

00:41:52.690 --> 00:41:54.262
or changing the way
things are graded

00:41:54.262 --> 00:41:55.720
or the weighting
of the grades that

00:41:55.720 --> 00:41:59.080
really aren't things
that can be changed

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:01.539
in the middle of a course.

00:42:01.539 --> 00:42:03.080
And while they might
be valid points,

00:42:03.080 --> 00:42:07.690
I feel like sometimes
a mid-course evaluation

00:42:07.690 --> 00:42:11.380
is going to solicit
comments that

00:42:11.380 --> 00:42:15.300
are not necessarily helpful
to that year of the course.

00:42:15.300 --> 00:42:18.289
And it might be more helpful--

00:42:18.289 --> 00:42:19.830
and those mid-year
comments are going

00:42:19.830 --> 00:42:23.490
to be more helpful really
for reminding students

00:42:23.490 --> 00:42:26.890
and collecting their thoughts
while their thoughts are still

00:42:26.890 --> 00:42:29.470
fresh on whatever
was being taught

00:42:29.470 --> 00:42:31.250
around that mid-year period.

00:42:31.250 --> 00:42:34.020
And so by the time you get to
the final course evaluation

00:42:34.020 --> 00:42:38.270
they haven't forgotten what
they were experiencing.

00:42:38.270 --> 00:42:39.650
Can I maybe follow up on that?

00:42:39.650 --> 00:42:41.410
I think that's a great point.

00:42:41.410 --> 00:42:43.430
A couple of the questions
that you guys did

00:42:43.430 --> 00:42:47.150
a wonderful job writing
to spoke to when

00:42:47.150 --> 00:42:50.020
is the most effective
time to ask for feedback?

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:52.100
And a couple people
suggested continuous.

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:54.450
Should it be a daily
journal that every day

00:42:54.450 --> 00:42:56.700
I go home and say,
this class was awesome,

00:42:56.700 --> 00:42:58.550
or I would have
changed this part?

00:42:58.550 --> 00:43:02.150
Or could it even be
fun in that context?

00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:03.650
Could it-- does it
always have to be

00:43:03.650 --> 00:43:08.180
an arduous end of the
year soul searching thing?

00:43:08.180 --> 00:43:12.980
Or can it be maybe a more
informal continuous thing?

00:43:12.980 --> 00:43:14.688
I just want to open that to you.

00:43:18.432 --> 00:43:19.700
Can I just add to that?

00:43:19.700 --> 00:43:22.880
Maybe even after
the course is over,

00:43:22.880 --> 00:43:27.245
allow some time to go by
so that you can really

00:43:27.245 --> 00:43:30.920
reflect on what are the
lasting effects of that course.

00:43:30.920 --> 00:43:36.890
I've had students who have
given a course a fair evaluation

00:43:36.890 --> 00:43:40.865
at the very end, thought
about it over the summer

00:43:40.865 --> 00:43:47.350
and come back and tell me it was
phenomenal because the takeaway

00:43:47.350 --> 00:43:49.840
filtered through.

00:43:49.840 --> 00:43:52.460
Those moments, those
high intensity moments

00:43:52.460 --> 00:43:55.620
that may have come from
the class at any moment.

00:43:55.620 --> 00:43:58.485
In fact, is that
more valuable for you

00:43:58.485 --> 00:44:03.110
to reflect on after
some time has passed

00:44:03.110 --> 00:44:08.080
and as you're maybe making
choices for what's the next--

00:44:08.080 --> 00:44:11.288
what are the next courses
that I'm going to be taking?

00:44:15.270 --> 00:44:18.640
I think I very much echo
exactly what you said.

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:20.635
I do think there is
some-- like right now

00:44:20.635 --> 00:44:23.350
the Q scores are solicited
right before students

00:44:23.350 --> 00:44:24.815
get their grades.

00:44:24.815 --> 00:44:29.010
I do think there is some
logistical difficulties in that

00:44:29.010 --> 00:44:31.570
once a student sees their
grade they may not feel

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:34.230
the same way about the course.

00:44:34.230 --> 00:44:36.300
But I do think that
there are definitely

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:37.860
courses that I have
taken here, which

00:44:37.860 --> 00:44:40.200
after teaching
subsequent courses,

00:44:40.200 --> 00:44:42.430
I feel so much more grateful
for having to take--

00:44:42.430 --> 00:44:44.480
I took MCD060 with Marty.

00:44:44.480 --> 00:44:46.290
And that course, I'm
so grateful for having

00:44:46.290 --> 00:44:48.880
taken because the
skills that I use

00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:52.320
are now invaluable in higher
level graduate bio courses

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:53.910
that I'm taking.

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:58.380
I think that in and of
itself is a useful to think

00:44:58.380 --> 00:45:01.530
about soliciting
feedback maybe a semester

00:45:01.530 --> 00:45:03.610
after you've taken a
class, after you've

00:45:03.610 --> 00:45:06.220
taken more advanced
classes in the same area.

00:45:06.220 --> 00:45:08.160
But that being said,
that doesn't necessarily

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:12.331
have to get rid of the Q
scores being collected right

00:45:12.331 --> 00:45:13.830
before the grades
because I do think

00:45:13.830 --> 00:45:15.829
that there is some value
to a student reflecting

00:45:15.829 --> 00:45:17.982
on the course before
getting something

00:45:17.982 --> 00:45:19.440
on their transcript
that tells them

00:45:19.440 --> 00:45:21.480
how they did in the course.

00:45:21.480 --> 00:45:23.340
Actually, that reminds
me of something

00:45:23.340 --> 00:45:26.310
that came up in the panel
this morning, which was

